title: For Sale:  100 Rounds 7.35 Carcano Ammo on Original Brass Breda Clips
postcontent:
Another neat discovery as I continue to sort through my 40 year collection of military goodies:100 rounds 7.35 Italian Carcano ammo loaded in original WWII era brass Breda machine gun clips packed in their original box. 

Ammo and clips are clean and in very nice shape. There are some dark spots intermittently on the brass but not many considering this ammo was made in 1939. 

Ammo itself is brass case with cupronickel jackets and it does attract s magnet. There are five 20 round clips in the box. 

The box is in fantastic shape and it's well & clearly marked. Box was sealed until I opened it to inspect the ammo and take these pictures. I had a hard time deciding on whether to open or not, but felt I needed to inspect everything before I listed it. 

This is quite collectible today and original 7.35 Carcano ammo sells for $45+ per 18 round box on GunBroker all the time. 

I believe this particular ammo is even more collectible & valuable loaded on the Breda clips in their original 1939 box. 

Asking Price is $200 with pickup in the Brandon area. I will ship (where legal) via UPS ground at buyers expense. Buyer must be at least 18 years old to purchase.

Action: FN SPR, .535 magnum bolt face, Right Hand, Short Action. Action and first 1.75 inches of barrel has been glass bedded with DevCon steel bedding. Stock: McMillan TMP adjustable- features sniper fill, adjustable length of pull and comb, extra front bipod stud, textured grip and fore end. Original black paint (was painted using camo spray paint which can be removed). This stock was designed for a government agency (I believe possibly for the FBI's HRT when they were testing the SPRs). Mcmillan only made a limited number of them. Barrel: Douglas air gauged #6 light target straight taper, .75 at muzzle, recessed target crown, 1:10 twist, chromoly. Rail: Picatinny, FN Manufacture. Rings: 30mm, MED height. They are of either IBA or Badger Ordnance manufacture. I cannot definitively recall but those are the only two sources of rings I purchase. Finish: Dark Charcoal Parkerizing. Note: there is a very thin scratch in the finish along the stock line on the non-bolt side of the action; presumably from when it was being glass bedded. Overall, the rifle is very comfortable to shoot and balances well in non-standard shooting positions. The rifle received a proper break in using a 1-1-1-1-1,5-5-5-5-5 procedure. It has less than 150 rounds through it. I do have all receipts for machine work upon request.  Thanks for your interest.
